      <text>by our experimental apparatus will drastically change the position and momentum of the electron—if the electron is in an atom, the very act of observing it with a gamma ray microscope may knock it out of the atom altogether.All this is true enough, and it does give a general idea of the impossibility of measuring precisely both the position and momentum of an electron. But what the uncertainty principle tells us is that, according to the fundamental equation of quantum mechanics, there is no such thing as an electron that possesses both a precise momentum and a precise position.</text>
