      <text>Feynman explains the basic recipe simply. In quantum mechanics, an “event” is a set of initial and final conditions, no more and no less. An electron leaves the gun on one side of our apparatus, and the electron arrives at a particular detector on the other side of the holes. That is an event. The probability of an event is given by the square of a number which is, essentially, Schrodinger’s wave function, ω. If there is more than one way in which the event can occur (both holes are open inside the experiment), then the probability</text>
      </fragment>
