      <text> of each possible event (the probability of the electron arriving at each chosen detector) is given by the square of the sum of the ω’s, and there is interference. But when we make an observation to find out which of the alternative possibilities actually happens (look to see which hole the electron goes through) the probability distribution is just the sum of the squares of the ω’s, and the interference term disappears—the wave function collapses.</text>
      </fragment>
